We have system of two equations with two unknowns, and so we know there will be exactly one solution if and only if there is no common solution to the pair-wise equation
\begin{align*}
2ax+2y&=b,\\
5x+y&=-3.
\end{align*}
When this is the case, we can eliminate $x,y$ by subtracting first equation from second.
\begin{align*}
5x+y&=-3\\
2ax+2y&=b
\end{align*}
So, subtracting subtraction from second subtraction gives us
\begin{align*}
(5x+y)-(2ax+2y)&=(-3)-b\\
\Rightarrow qx&=(-3)-b\\
\Rightarrow x&=\frac{-3-b}{q}
\end{align*} 
Let’s plug in $x=\frac{-3-b}{q}$ into the first equation.
\begin{align*}
2a\left(\frac{-3-b}{q}\right)+2y&=b\\
\Rightarrow -6-2b+2aq+2y&=b\\
\Rightarrow 2aq+2y&=b+6+2b\\
\Rightarrow 2aq+2y&=3b+6\\
\Rightarrow qx+y&=3b+6\tag{1}
\end{align*}  
Let’s plug in $x=\frac{-3-b}{q}$ into the second equation.
\begin{align*}
5\left(\frac{-3-b}{q}\right)+y&=-3\\
\Rightarrow -15-5b+q+y&=-3\\
\Rightarrow y&=3b-12\\
\Rightarrow y&=3b-12\tag{2}
\end{align*}  
Plug $y$ from$(2)$ into equation$(1)$ to get
\begin{align*}
q\left(\frac{-3-b}{q}\right)+(3b-12)&=3b+6\\
\Rightarrow-3-b+3b-12&=3b+6\\
\Rightarrow -12&=6\\
\Rightarrow -2&=1
\end{align*}  
This is contradiction. Therefore, system of two equation would have infinite solutions  to this, since these two equations  are not linearly independent.
